---
import ChapterLayout from "../layouts/ChapterLayout.astro";
import BinderHoles from "../components/BinderHoles.astro";
import Backlink from "../components/Backlink.astro";
---

<ChapterLayout title="Performance Evaluation" headVoice="publisher">
  <div data-voice="publisher">
    <BinderHoles />
    <Backlink />
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        During your time with Lumon, you stand to climb
        a most sacred ladder of departmental standing, responsibility, and trust.
      </p>
      <p>
        In
        <a href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a>
        , the rungs of that ladder are called
        <strong>Kier Points</strong>, and this chapter shares the secrets to earning them.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Earning Kier Points</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >There is no fixed schedule for the awarding of Kier Points. Your
      </span><strong><span>GM</span></strong><span>
        grants them at moments of genuine significance, when an employee&#x27;s
        conduct has meaningfully served the interests of Lumon Industries.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>Earning a Point is a </span><em><span>story beat</span></em><span
        >, not a bookkeeping chore — your GM is encouraged to make the moment
        land. A few examples of conduct worthy of a Kier Point:</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span
            >Meeting one&#x27;s quota for a full quarter without a single
            misstep.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span
            >Volunteering for an unpleasant task that no other employee would
            accept.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span
            >Quietly settling a dispute between coworkers before it reached the
            ears of management.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span
            >A display of loyalty so exemplary that the Floor Manager pulls the
            employee aside to thank them personally.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Where the Point Goes</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span>Every Kier Point is placed into a </span><strong
        ><span>specific row</span></strong
      ><span> of the </span><strong><span>Temper Analysis Chart</span></strong
      ><span> on the LIEP — the row whose </span><strong
        ><span>Temper</span></strong
      ><span> drove the qualifying action.</span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>An employee who won a tense meeting through sharp </span><strong
        ><span>WIT</span></strong
      ><span> (parent Temper: </span><strong><span>DREAD</span></strong><span
        >) earns their Point in the
      </span><strong><span>DREAD</span></strong><span>
        row. An employee who soothed a hard moment with practiced
      </span><strong><span>CHEER</span></strong><span>
        (parent Temper:
      </span><strong><span>FROLIC</span></strong><span
        >) earns theirs in the
      </span><strong><span>FROLIC</span></strong><span>
        row. When more than one Temper might apply, your GM&#x27;s call is
        final.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="info">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
          <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
          <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><strong><u><span>Why row placement matters</span></u></strong></p>
        <p>
          <span
            >Points placed in a row are added to that row&#x27;s Core Principle
            Rolls — see
          </span><strong><span>The Roll</span></strong><span> in </span><a
            href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a
          ><span
            >. Row placement turns your roleplay choices into mechanical
            specialization: the shape of an employee&#x27;s career becomes the
            shape of their character sheet.</span
          >
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Determining Tier</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span>An employee&#x27;s current </span><strong><span>Tier</span></strong
      ><span> is the </span><em><span>total</span></em><span>
        number of Kier Points they hold, summed across all four Temper rows.</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong><span>1 – 2 Points</span></strong><span> — Tier I</span></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong><span>3 – 4 Points</span></strong><span> — Tier II</span></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>5 – 6 Points</span></strong><span> — Tier III</span>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong><span>7 – 8 Points</span></strong><span> — Tier IV</span></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong><span>9 – 10 Points</span></strong><span> — Tier V</span></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <span>Each Tier carries a set of </span><strong><span>Boons</span></strong
      ><span>
        — narrative permissions and mechanical privileges that persist for as
        long as you hold the Points that earned them. Drop a Tier, and its Boons
        drop with you.</span
      >
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>The Kier Track</span></h2>
    <p><em><span>The Corporate Path.</span></em></p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Lumon recognizes those who exemplify our values, and the Kier Track is
        that recognition made visible. Climb it, and the company opens its doors
        to you.</span
      >
    </p>
    <h3><span>Tier I — Associate</span></h3>
    <p><span>A standard employee in good standing.</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Basic departmental access.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>Eligible for standard employee benefits.</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3><span>Tier II — Senior Associate</span></h3>
    <p><span>A proven and dependable employee.</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Access to personnel records.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>Trusted with sensitive departmental information.</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3><span>Tier III — Distinguished Associate</span></h3>
    <p><span>An employee recognized for exceptional performance.</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Access to restricted departmental resources.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>May request special corporate accommodations.</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3><span>Tier IV — Chief Associate</span></h3>
    <p><span>The highest-ranking associate within the department.</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Restrictions</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span
              >Only one employee may hold this title at a time. Should two
              employees qualify, the GM may stage an internal competition, or
              arbitrate the placement narratively.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Access to department-wide records.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>May sponsor privileges for other employees.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span
              >Considered the primary employee representative of the department.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3><span>Tier V — Department Chief</span></h3>
    <p><span>The official leader of the department.</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Restrictions</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Only one employee may hold this title at a time.</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Full departmental access.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>Access to executive communications.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>Authority to authorize departmental initiatives.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>Direct communication with management.</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h4><span>Kier Philosophy</span></h4>
    <p>
      <span>Kier advancement grants </span><strong
        ><span>official power</span></strong
      ><span>
        — recognition, trust, access, responsibility, and authority. The Kier
        Track rewards those who excel within the system.</span
      >
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Losing Kier Points</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span
        >Kier Points may be lost as readily as they are earned. An employee
        found to have acted against the company&#x27;s interests — a prohibited
        item discovered at their station, a confidence betrayed, a record found
        altered — may forfeit Points at the GM&#x27;s discretion.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >The GM decides how many Points are lost, and from which row, according
        to what occurred and how plainly it was seen. Should the loss drop an
        employee below a Tier threshold, the Tier falls with them, and its Boons
        are revoked.</span
      >
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Demerits and Termination</span></h2>
    <p>
      <strong><span>Demerits</span></strong><span>
        are tracked separately from Kier Points. They accumulate toward
      </span><strong><span>Termination</span></strong><span> (see </span><strong
        ><span>Burnout</span></strong
      ><span> in </span><a href="/procedural-guidelines"
        >Procedural Guidelines</a
      ><span>).</span>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >A Demerit is most often issued as a consequence of Burnout. The GM may
        also issue one at any time should an employee do something Lumon judges
        unforgivable, even absent Burnout.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >Three Demerits remains the threshold for Termination. A loss of Kier
        Points may accompany a Demerit, but does not replace one.</span
      >
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>On Advancement and &quot;Winning&quot;</span></h2>
    <p>
      <span>Reaching Department Chief is not &quot;winning.&quot; </span><a
        href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a
      ><span>
        has no win condition and no finish line. The Tiers exist to
      </span><em><span>equip</span></em><span>
        your employee; the story your GM builds, and the choices you make within
        it, are the game itself. Advancement is a tool, never a trophy.</span
      >
    </p>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2><span>The Ricken Track</span></h2>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong><span>Dear reader,</span></strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >Lumon has shown you their ladder. Climb it, and they will trust
              you, promote you, and love you — right up until the day you climb
              high enough to see what you have been serving.</span
            ></em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >There is another ladder. Lumon would pull this guide from every
              shelf for printing it, so I have printed it myself, by hand, in
              the copies I could reach. I call it the
            </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>Ricken Track</span></strong></em><em
            ><span>, after the one book on this floor worth reading.</span></em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >The machinery is the same as theirs: you earn a Point in a moment
              that matters, you place it in the row of the Temper that drove the
              act, and you sum your Points for your Tier. Lumon already drilled
              you on all that. What changes is everything it is
            </span></em
          ><em><u><span>for</span></u></em><em
            ><span
              >. Where Kier rewards obedience with badges, Ricken rewards
              curiosity with knowledge and contraband.</span
            ></em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >One warning before you read on. Lumon does not love its critics.
              This Track is more dangerous than theirs — and walking both at
              once grows more dangerous the further you have come on each.</span
            ></em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— Concerned Citizen</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <em
        ><span
          >The Resistance Path. (Yes, this whole section is mine. Read it before
          someone takes this copy from you.)</span
        ></em
      >
    </p>
    <h3><span>Tier I — Reader</span></h3>
    <p>
      <span>You&#x27;ve found something you weren&#x27;t meant to read.</span>
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Learn a secret rumor from the GM.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>Gain access to a hidden stash location.</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u><span>Persistent Contraband</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>A hidden note, page, or document.</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3><span>Tier II — Correspondent</span></h3>
    <p><span>You&#x27;ve established contact beyond your department.</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Access to interdepartmental information.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>Ability to receive hidden messages.</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u><span>Persistent Contraband</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>Unauthorized keycard, or a hidden communication channel.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3><span>Tier III — Conspirator</span></h3>
    <p><span>You&#x27;ve become part of an underground network.</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Access to restricted employee information.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>May call upon underground contacts for assistance.</span></p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u><span>Persistent Contraband</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span
              >Unauthorized department maps, or a record of hidden routes.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3><span>Tier IV — Agitator</span></h3>
    <p><span>Your actions actively influence the resistance.</span></p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Access to multiple underground contacts.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>Ability to establish safe locations.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p><span>Ability to conceal evidence from management.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>Once per </span><strong><span>workday</span></strong><span
              >, temporarily suppress the effects of a
            </span><strong><span>Problem</span></strong><span>.</span>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u><span>Persistent Contraband</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span
              >A secret contact list, or the address of a hidden meeting
              location.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3><span>Tier V — Awakener</span></h3>
    <p>
      <span>You possess knowledge capable of threatening Lumon itself.</span>
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p><strong><u><span>Boons</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p><span>Ability to establish underground cells.</span></p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>Ability to reveal hidden truths to other employees.</span>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>Once per </span><strong><span>workday</span></strong><span
              >, gain
            </span><strong><span>Confidence</span></strong><span>
              on any action involving Lumon secrets.</span
            >
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong><u><span>Persistent Contraband</span></u></strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <span>Forbidden archives, or a high-security stolen resource.</span>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h4><span>Ricken Philosophy</span></h4>
    <p>
      <span>Ricken advancement grants </span><strong
        ><span>unofficial power</span></strong
      ><span>
        — secrets, connections, leverage, and knowledge. The Ricken Track
        rewards those who look beyond the system.</span
      >
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Contraband</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span
        >Contraband is the currency of the resistance — the physical and
        informational scraps Lumon never meant you to hold. It comes in two
        forms.</span
      >
    </p>
    <h3><span>Persistent Contraband</span></h3>
    <p>
      <span
        >Persistent Contraband is granted by the Ricken Track at each new Tier.
        As long as the employee holds the Tier, they hold the Contraband.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >When a Roll would be meaningfully aided by a relevant piece of
        Persistent Contraband, the GM may choose one of:</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Waive the Roll entirely</span></strong><span>
            — the action just succeeds. (You have the keycard. The door opens.)</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong
            ><span>Reduce the Roll&#x27;s Task Severity by one tier</span
            ></strong
          ><span>
            — Arduous becomes Demanding, Demanding becomes Routine, and so on.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong><span>Grant Confidence</span></strong><span>
            on the Roll.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <span
        >If an employee drops a Tier, the GM decides which piece of Persistent
        Contraband is lost — and how. A keycard demagnetizes. A map is
        discovered by Security. A contact stops returning calls. The world finds
        a way.</span
      >
    </p>
    <h3><span>Consumable Contraband</span></h3>
    <p>
      <span
        >Consumable Contraband exists in the world independent of any Track. Any
        employee may find Consumable Contraband — by stumbling across it, by
        being given it, or by deliberately seeking it out. The GM controls
        availability.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span>A Consumable item is </span><strong><span>spent</span></strong><span
      >
        for a guaranteed
      </span><strong><span>Success</span></strong><span>
        on a single related Roll, or to bypass a single specific obstacle.
        Examples include a smuggled note containing a one-time-use password
        recovery key, a smuggled snack that restores one stress, or a frail
        keycard that looks like it's about to snap.</span
      >
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong><span>Hold it close.</span></strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><span
              >Persistent or Consumable, any Contraband Lumon finds on you is
              taken — and the GM may hand down a
            </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>Demerit</span></strong></em><em
            ><span>, a loss of </span></em
          ><em><strong><span>Kier Points</span></strong></em><em
            ><span
              >, or both, depending on how plainly you were caught holding it.
              Carry it carefully. Carry it rarely.</span
            ></em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong><span>— C.C.</span></strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Losing Ricken Points</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span
        >Points can be lost as well as earned — on my Track as much as theirs.
        You lose Ricken Points when those who trust you come to see you as too
        cosy with Lumon: accepting a promotion in plain view, naming a coworker
        to management, reporting a rumor you should have buried. Trust is the
        only currency the resistance has, and it can be spent away.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >The GM decides how many you lose, and from which row, by what you did
        and who saw it. Fall below a Tier, and the Tier falls with you — its
        Boons and its Persistent Contraband gone.</span
      >
    </p>
    <hr />
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Two Paths, Shared Destinations</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span
        >My Track and theirs mirror one another. At equal Tiers, they often
        reach the same destinations — just through different doors.</span
      >
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Official Keycard</span></strong><span>
              &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            </span><strong><span>Stolen Keycard</span></strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Department Records</span></strong><span>
              &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            </span><strong><span>Secret Records</span></strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Promotion</span></strong><span>
              &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            </span><strong><span>Conspiracy</span></strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Authority</span></strong><span>
              &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            </span><strong><span>Leverage</span></strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Resources</span></strong><span>
              &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            </span><strong><span>Secrets</span></strong>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <strong><span>Trust</span></strong><span>
              &nbsp;↔&nbsp;
            </span><strong><span>Knowledge</span></strong>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      <span
        >A Tier V Kier employee and a Tier V Ricken employee may ultimately
        stand in the same room. The Kier employee walks through the front door,
        because they are
      </span><em><span>authorized</span></em><span
        >. The Ricken employee finds a way in, because they
      </span><em><span>discovered a route nobody else knows exists</span></em
      ><span>.</span>
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2><span>Walking Both Ladders</span></h2>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <span
        >Nothing stops you from climbing both ladders at once. Some of the
        bravest people I have known did exactly that. But understand the cost:
        the further you climb on one, the harder the other fights you. A trusted
        manager is watched for betrayal. A known troublemaker is never offered
        the promotion.</span
      >
    </p>
    <p>
      <span
        >When you reach for Points on one Track while the other is already well
        climbed, expect the GM to make you work for it:</span
      >
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>A higher </span><strong><span>Task Severity</span></strong><span
          >
            on any Roll involved.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><span>A Roll demanded where one would normally be waived.</span></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <span>Fresh </span><strong
            ><span>opportunities for discovery</span></strong
          ><span>
            — Lumon&#x27;s eyes notice contradictions, and the resistance
            notices fence-sitters.</span
          >
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
